A tee-see-pee-eye-pee refresher.

To read most networking output, you need three layers clear in your head: the address, the port, and the protocol. The eye-pee address is a number that identifies a machine on a network. In version four it is four numbers from zero to two fifty-five separated by dots, like one-ninety-two dot one-sixty-eight dot one dot forty-two. In version six it is eight groups of hexadecimal separated by colons. Every interface gets at least one address.

A port is a number that identifies a specific service on a machine. Web servers usually listen on port eighty for plain web traffic and four forty-three for secure web; s-s-h listens on twenty-two. The combination of an address and a port uniquely names a network endpoint. And the protocol is how the two ends actually talk. Tee-see-pee is connection-oriented, reliable, and ordered, used by most services like the web and s-s-h. You-dee-pee is connectionless, fast, and lossy, used by things like dee-en-ess and video streaming where speed matters more than perfect delivery.

A little on addressing. A version-four address is thirty-two bits, and a network is a range of those addresses, written in what is called sider notation: the address, a slash, and a prefix length. A slash twenty-four, for example, is a typical home network of two hundred fifty-six addresses. Three ranges, the ten range, part of the one-seventy-two range, and the one-ninety-two-one-sixty-eight range, are private; they are never routed on the public internet, so home and corporate networks all use them. Finally, a gateway, or default gateway, is the address packets are sent to when their destination is not on your local network, usually your router. Without a default gateway you can reach local machines but nothing on the wider internet. For the exam you do not need to be a network engineer; just understand the address, port, and protocol model, what a slash twenty-four means, and that you need a gateway to reach beyond the local network.
